<subSubSection id="5C252FF08F9E39839488AFF39F8D8776" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="8D6DC76AF37488C4E8FEAF975099CD86" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="101BFCC2F235A8C7D1750CE456FAED88" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">
The strongly recessed and microsculptured epistoma (Fig. 26A) and reduced labrum, in combination with the strongly convex frons is unique to this species, as is the pattern of elytral striae, with only the 2nd stria complete, the 1st and 3rd striae abbreviated from the apex, and the 4th and 5th striae absent (Fig. 26B). The following species, 
<taxonomicName id="A63689FB15A39DAED9EF3BC0C8EF6A39" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Baconia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Baconia crassa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassa">Baconia crassa</taxonomicName>
, is very similar, having a microsculptured epistoma, but has the frons depressed in the middle, a complete 1st elytral stria, and a more nearly complete inner metaventral stria.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="02E945FA06B299970F11B9AE60E20602" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="A91510D5A2D66B22E076C56DD80A2771" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CE98B5FB2D37EB196A2672E3677A8B44" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">This species is named for its swollen frons.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
